Demonstration of point-to-point communication between two processors.

This program uses `MPI_Send` and `MPI_Recv` to send an integer value from
process-0 to process-1.

These two function perform "blocking" send and receive, respectively, that is,
the program halts further executtion until the send or the recv operation is
done. In other words, a call to these functions does not return control back to
the caller until the operation is done. It would be unsafe if it returned
immediately, because, for instance, we wouldn't know whether it's safe to read
the receive buffer or write to the send buffer.

> One can think of message transfer as consisting of the following phases:
    1. Data is pulled out of the send buffer and a message is assembled.
    2. A message is transferred from sender to receiver.
    3. Data is pulled from the incoming messge and disassembled into the
       receive buffer.

NOTE
    A call to `MPI_Send` must be accompanied by a call to `MPI_Recv`; otherwise
    a deadlock may occur.

NOTE
    When sending and receiving, the send and receive data types of the message
    that is being transferred must match.

NOTE
    There are also two variants of send and recv: `MPI_Send_c` and
    `MPI_Recv_c`. These functions accept the message count as MPI_Count rather
    than int. MPI_Count simply has a bigger range than int. These variants are
    available in OpenMPI; MPICH is an implementation that does provide them.

MPI_Recv allows wildcard values: MPI_ANY_SOURCE, and MPI_ANY_TAG, to accept any
source and any tag. This is useful if you care neither about the tag nor the
source.

We could inspect the status of receive operation using status object. This is
particularly useful if we use the above wildcards.

    recv_status.error
    recv_status.source
    recv_status.tag
